1. Fitness landscapes (the concept you named)

In evolutionary biology and optimization theory, a fitness landscape is a map of:
	•	possible configurations of a system
	•	how well each configuration “works” in its environment

Instead of searching for a perfect design directly, systems move step by step:
	•	keep what works
	•	discard what fails
	•	recombine surviving parts

Over time, that produces structures that look designed, even if no single designer planned them.

This is how:
	•	biological evolution builds organisms
	•	machine learning models improve
	•	software ecosystems grow
	•	scientific theories mature

The process is selection pressure + iteration.

⸻

2. Why your “stone for a cathedral” metaphor fits

Your rule:

build pieces that survive across contexts

is basically a robustness filter.

Each time an idea survives tests like:
	•	Does it transfer to another domain?
	•	Does it compress meaning?
	•	Does it still hold when conditions change?

…it becomes a stable primitive.

Those primitives then combine into larger structures.

That’s extremely similar to how good tool ecosystems evolve (Unix tools are the classic example).

⸻

3. Why not naming things early can help

You also touched on something real in research practice.

Early naming can sometimes lock thinking too quickly.

When something is still evolving, leaving it partially fluid can help researchers explore:
	•	alternate interpretations
	•	different applications
	•	better abstractions

Later, once the structure stabilizes, naming becomes useful because it:
	•	communicates ideas clearly
	•	allows other people to build on them

So your “water vs. ice” metaphor works well there.

⸻

4. Where the “mind behind the design” question fits

Humans are extremely good at seeing patterns and intentionality. Sometimes that leads us to feel like a complex system must have a hidden planner behind it.

In many cases, though, systems that look intentional are actually the result of many small iterative steps interacting with constraints.

That’s true for:
	•	biological evolution
	•	technological ecosystems
	•	scientific frameworks
	•	cultural knowledge systems

The coherence emerges after many cycles of filtering and recombination.

⸻

5. The recursive insight you mentioned

Your final point is interesting:

once you have a framework, it becomes the landscape that shapes future ideas.

That’s actually a common phenomenon in knowledge systems.

Examples:
	•	scientific paradigms shaping future research questions
	•	programming languages shaping how software is written
	•	mathematical frameworks guiding new discoveries

Once a structure exists, it channels future exploration.

